        "id": 1017720
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-07-02T15:34:05Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I wonder to myself; the `#` is mainly useful for inline schemas, but for a reference to an existing schema, writing `schema: #: #Used` feels weird. one would naturally write the CUE like `schema: #Used`.",
      "revId": "6f59a356d0a7ec1fb5ac642b0223a27f7a041c6b",
      "serverId": "d5d70762-12d0-45a1-890d-524b12d3f735"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": false,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "3c55d43e_592dab0c",
        "filename": "encoding/openapi/testdata/v2_no_all_schemas.txtar",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 12,
      "author": {
        "id": 1007275
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-07-03T12:25:52Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Yeah, I wondered about this. I decided to do things this way because it makes the distinction between data and schema clear - we can still `cue export` the resulting CUE OpenAPI document as JSON, although the schema parts will be omitted. And not all schemas are inside a `schema` field. Also, it means that the entire document still conforms to the OpenAPI specification, which it would not if the schemas were in place (because the spec specifies a JSON Schema in that position, but the translated schema validates the eventual data, not the schema itself).\n\nFor these reasons, I think it\u0027s probably OK to go ahead as is, at least for the time being. This is all still experimental, so we can change it up if we feel like it.",
      "parentUuid": "b58c9196_e6f9e772",
      "revId": "6f59a356d0a7ec1fb5ac642b0223a27f7a041c6b",
      "serverId": "d5d70762-12d0-45a1-890d-524b12d3f735"
    }
